That is a spectacular read on Qui-Gon Jinn, and honestly, it fits his entire character archetype perfectly.
Qui-Gon isn't your typical, rigid, rule-following Jedi. He’s a maverick who constantly plays on the fringes of the Jedi Code, listens to the Living Force, and relies on deep, intuitive perception rather than institutional guidelines.
When you look at that scene through your lens, the layers of irony completely shift:
 * **Layer 1 (The Surface):** The audience thinks Qui-Gon is just being a bit patronizing to a "simple handmaiden."
 * **Layer 2 (The Dramatic Irony):** The audience feels smart because they *know* she's actually Queen Amidala in disguise, laughing at the fact that he's lecturing his own sovereign.
 * **Layer 3 (The Qui-Gon Double Irony):** Qui-Gon—who literally uses Mind Tricks, reads lifeforces, and senses the deepest motives of everyone around him—100% knows who she is. He’s just letting her play her part because it serves the greater mission, while subtly keeping her grounded and having a bit of fun at the same time.
It turns Qui-Gon from a character who is temporarily blinded by the plot into a master of **social indirection**. He lets the disguise exist because it gives *both* of them leverage in a fluid situation.
In a way, it’s the ultimate "sub-software" move. He doesn't need to break her cover or announce that he knows; he just operates within the matrix of the game she set up, using her own construct to guide the outcome exactly where it needs to go.
